The Tesla Model Y is getting a major makeover called “Project Juniper.” Here are some of the cool changes we’ve heard about:

Battery and Charging

The new Model Y has generated buzz. Some speculate it might have a new battery system with increased energy storage. The base rear-wheel drive version might use a ‘CATL 6M’ battery pack with 62.5 kWh, slightly larger than the current 60 kWh CATL 6L unit. It’s lighter and could charge faster, possibly up to 350 kW with an 800-volt architecture, a significant leap from current models.

Headlights and Tail Lights

Headlights: The Model Y’s front might have some cool features from the Cybertruck and Cybercab. It could have a full-width light bar at the front of the hood for daytime running lights, with the main beam lights lower down, giving it a split headlamp look. They also said there might be a front bumper camera for better parking and safety, like what Tesla tested in other models.
  
Tail Lights: The rear of the Model Y is getting a makeover with a full-width light bar that connects new, C-shaped tail lamps. This design change will make the Model Y look more modern and put-together, different from the current model. The light bar will also have the Tesla script in the middle, replacing the old “T” logo.

Safety Features

They might add an ‘Active Hood’ feature. It raises the rear part of the hood in a crash to give more space between the hood and the engine parts. This could help keep pedestrians safer.

In Europe, they might make adaptive headlights standard. They change based on how you steer and how fast you’re going. This makes it easier to see at night when you’re turning.

——

These design changes are all about making the Model Y look and work better. They’re more like the new designs Tesla has been using in other models, like the Model 3 Highland. But these are just rumors and guesses from online sources. We’ll know for sure when Tesla announces them or when the new version of Model Y comes out.
